title: Green Lake Library Branch, 1906
description: From Green Lake's "About the Branch" article on spl.org: "Library service in Green Lake dates back to 1905, when The Seattle Public Library opened a small, one-room structure on the east side of the lake, several blocks south of the present building. The structure was built on a wooden platform. A board sidewalk led from the street and the streetcar tracks to the library. In rainy weather, the tiny building was surrounded by mud and water and young boys begged the librarian for twine so they could fish over the railing."
subjects: Seattle Public Library. Green Lake Branch

title: Waterfront from Marion St. to Union St., ca. 1868
description: View from Elliott Bay between Marion St. and Union St. The white building along the water is the Occidental Brotherhood Building which was located at the base of Madison St. The First Methodist Protestant Church appears further up and to the left, followed by the Territorial University.

title: Temperance Hall on E. 72nd St., 1891
description: HistoryLink article "Green Lake School" states: "As a temporary measure to meet the growing needs of the 1,000 residents living nearby, in 1901 the school district opened two annexes at Green Lake. The first, about which little is known, was located on the site of the John Marshall school and provided space for two classrooms. The other occupied the two-story I.O.G.T. Hall at today's (1999) NE 72nd Street and 5th Avenue NE, above Baskin & Robbins. This temperance hall was home for three class rooms of second through fifth grade children during the 1901-02 school year."
subjects: Independent Order of Good Templars. Grand Lodge of Washington. Lodge No. 1 (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Bakery and Confectionery Workers Union local no. 9, ca. 1903

title: Librarian checking out books at Central Library, June 6, 1953
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Mrs. D. D. Gillispie [Gillespie] (librarian) checks in books in main lobby. Mrs. A. F. Pripp. Mr. Harold Simmons." The 1953 city directory lists a Dewey D. Gillespie with a wife named Jean K. The 1953 Library Circulation Department report confirms that Jean worked at the library as a clerk. The city directory also lists Margaret Pripp, wife to Alvin F. Pripp.

description: Broadway High School (then named the Seattle High School) opened in 1902. The high school closed in 1946 and reopened as the Broadway-Edison Technical School. The Edison Technical School incorporated with the Seattle Central Community College in 1966. The only original school structure that still stands as of 2017 is the Performance Hall.

title: James St. and Yesler Way, ca. 1867
description: Intersection of James St., Front St. (now 1st Ave.) and Mill St. (now Yesler Way). The Daily Post building appears on the right. The three trees located in front of the building were used for a lynching on January 18, 1882. Buildings on the left side include the Occidental Hotel, the Vanity Fair Saloon, Frach grocery store, Mackintosh and Reeves Bank, Gem Saloon (Charlie Anderson, proprietor) and a drug store (Gardner Kellogg).

title: Boater on Green Lake, ca. 1910
description: South shore of Green Lake. Person in boat and person hanging off side of boat. The streetcar and homes are visible on the lake's far shore.

description: The filling of Green Lake began in 1911 as part of John Olmstead's design plan. The fill added roughly 100 acres of additional land to the park.

title: Woodland Court Apartments, ca. 1930
description: A September 9, 1917 Seattle Times article celebrating the opening of the apartments stated: "Of a distinctive type of modern apartment building is Woodland Court at the southeast corner of North Fiftieth Street and Fremont Avenue, at the main or boulevard entrance to Woodland Park, just completed by the Goodwin Real Estate at a cost of more than $45,000. The building has many novel attractions and was designed by George W. Lawton, well-known Seattle architect. It contains eighteen apartments of four and five rooms each, many with built-in glass sunrooms, or sleeping porches. The building is of solid brick construction, three stories and basement, covering a plot of ground 150 feet by 200 feet."

title: Green Lake School, 1906
description: School now referred to as Green Lake Elementary.

title: Intelligencer Office near 1st Ave. and Cherry St., ca. 1876
description: Constructed by Henry Yesler in 1874, this building served as an office for the Seattle Intelligencer Newspaper (which would later evolve into the Seattle Post-Intelligencer.)  The annotation on the photo "Founded by Higgins & Maxwell" refers to Samuel L. Maxwell and David Higgins who were early owners of the paper. The annotation elect "Judge Ike Hall" likely refers to Isaac Hall who served as one of the city's first attorneys and was involved with several unsuccessful attempts at newpaper publishing.

title: Dexter Horton home, ca. 1870
description: Dexter Horton home at 4th and Spring. It's possible that this structure predates the larger home that was built by the Hortons in 1873 at 3rd and Seneca.

subjects: East Green Lake Way North (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Works Progress Administration sign at Green Lake, March 12, 1937
description: HistoryLink article "Green Lake cleanup and redesign begins in 1936" states: "In the winter of 1936, a major, WPA-funded clean-up of Seattle's Green Lake is undertaken. For decades, the lake has been subject to algae bloom and outbreaks of green scum and foul odor, and swimmers have gotten swimmer's itch. The massive project includes dredging the lake, building an island (Swan Island, or Duck Island) as a wildlife sanctuary, and building a water-aerating fountain in the middle of the lake. The fountain is never built, but other parts of the project are carried out."

title: 1st Ave. S. north from S. Main St., 1877
description: Transcribed from image: "West side of Commercial St. [later 1st Ave.] between Washington and Main. Seattle 1877." Description from the same photo in the University of Washington's Asahel Curtis Collection: "Location depicted is west side between S. Washington St. and S. Main St. Original photographer unknown; copied by Theodore Peiser [10075]. Shows W. A. Jennings, groceries, the San Francisco Store (Toklas and Singerman, props.), Hall Paulson & Co., furniture, L. A. Treen, boots and shoes. According to Peiser, people standing on walk, left to right, are: (1) unknown; (2) George Reynolds; (3) Lew Parsons; (4) Jesse George; (5) unknown; (6) Melody Choir. According to Prosch, Seattle Album 1, p.22, the bystanders here are Wm. A. Jennings, Ed. Reynolds, George Finn, Frank Rummer, Melody Choir, Paul Singerman, D. B. Jackson, Bailey Gatzert and others."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

Building, located at 8016 Greenwood Ave. is Seattle's first public library branch to be constructed in 33 years."

title: R. Metz and Church in Israel member discussing the body of the Church's leader, Daniel Sawlt's, June 1929
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Religion and Sanitation Clash in Seattle. Seattle, Wash. A member of "The Church in Israel" talking with R. Metz of the Seattle Sanitation and Health Department following Metz's demand that the body of Daniel Salwt, prophet of the Israel organization be removed from their church and taken to an undertaking establishment. The disciples had refused to have the body touched saying it would interfere with resurrection. The dispute ended when the churchmen allowed the body to be removed on condition that it would not be embalmed for a certain period and that they be allowed to watch over it. R-6-20-29. EHP."
